    <item>
      <title>Denmark Strait</title>
      <link>https://malmans2.github.io/project/denmark-strait/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://malmans2.github.io/project/denmark-strait/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Ocean currents affecting the global climate are sustained by cold and dense water that sinks in the North Atlantic Ocean. A large portion of this water passes through Denmark Strait, the ocean channel located between Greenland and Iceland.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The amount of water entering the strait varies from day to day, and is controlled by ocean vortices. Knowing the mechanisms associated with these vortices is of key importance for understanding and predicting Earth’s climate. This figure shows vortices simulated using a high-resolution, realistic, general circulation model:













&lt;figure&gt;


  &lt;a data-fancybox=&#34;&#34; href=&#34;./almansi2020.jpg&#34; data-caption=&#34;Adapted from Almansi et al., 2020&#34;&gt;
&lt;img data-src=&#34;./almansi2020.jpg&#34; class=&#34;lazyload&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; &gt;&lt;/a&gt;


  
  
  &lt;figcaption&gt;
    Adapted from Almansi et al., 2020
  &lt;/figcaption&gt;


&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Several currents interact with each other and with the seafloor in Denmark Strait. We can disentangle different pathways by seeding and tracking virtual particles in our model. This animation shows how the temperature of water particles changes during their journey:&lt;br&gt;

&lt;div style=&#34;position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;&#34;&gt;
  &lt;iframe src=&#34;https://player.vimeo.com/video/296949375&#34; style=&#34;position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; border:0;&#34; title=&#34;vimeo video&#34; webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Much of my research consists of combining and comparing model output with observations. I’ve joined an exciting and unique cruise part of the Iceland-Greenland Seas Project (IGP), a multi-disciplinary program to study the air-sea interaction in winter:













